{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17629139","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17629139"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:03:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:03:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17253"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17253","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17253"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9943"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77906"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9943","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9943"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17253"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63384"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"7734"},{"type":"tags","id":"10754"},{"type":"tags","id":"10769"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23306"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23315"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77906","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77906"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA research team analyses height variation in a large Australian population. Their findings show that height follows a normal distribution and has an estimated heritability of 80%. Genome-wide association studies identify multiple genetic loci, with each locus accounting for less than 1% of the total phenotypic variance.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the type of genetic inheritance demonstrated by these findings?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Autosomal dominant inheritance","Mitochondrial inheritance","Polygenic inheritance","X-linked recessive inheritance","Y-linked inheritance"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis pattern represents \u003Cstrong\u003Epolygenic inheritance\u003C/strong\u003E, where multiple genes each contribute small additive effects to create a continuous phenotype distribution. The normal distribution and high heritability are characteristic features of polygenic traits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAutosomal dominant inheritance\u003C/strong\u003E - This would show a clear bimodal distribution of affected and unaffected individuals\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMitochondrial inheritance\u003C/strong\u003E - This shows maternal transmission patterns and typically affects energy-dependent tissues\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EX-linked recessive inheritance\u003C/strong\u003E - This shows sex-specific patterns with males more commonly affected\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EY-linked inheritance\u003C/strong\u003E - This would only affect males and show father-to-son transmission\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn polygenic inheritance, the combined effects of many genes plus environmental factors produce a range of phenotypes that follow a normal distribution in the population. The high heritability (80%) indicates that genetic factors explain most of the population variance in height.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Polygenic inheritance occurs when multiple genes contribute small additive effects to create a continuous phenotype distribution.","Traits showing polygenic inheritance typically follow a normal (Gaussian) distribution in the population.","Heritability in polygenic traits represents the proportion of phenotypic variance explained by genetic factors."],"references":["Turnpenny PD, Ellard S. Emery\u0027s Elements of Medical Genetics E-Book: Elsevier Health Sciences; 2011"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63384"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17253"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63384","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63384"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-08T20:33:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-08T20:36:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9943"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77906"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4945","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4945"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddec","name":"Genetics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-21T13:05:38+1